## No code without approved plan

Do not write or modify code until an implementation plan has been created and explicitly approved.

Documentation-only changes may be made after a documentation plan.

Research-only tasks must not modify production code.

## Flexity architecture layers

Flexity architecture is layered:

    Flexity Core
    -> Universal modules
    -> Industry template / industry package
    -> Tenant customization

Definitions:

- platform_core:
  Core tenancy, auth, permissions, shared infra, billing, common API patterns.

- universal_module:
  CRM, documents, payments, tasks, notifications, analytics, files, comments, audit log.

- industry_template:
  Seed/configuration layer for a specific industry, such as kindergarten_basic.

- industry_package:
  Deeper domain package with models, routes, services, workflows specific to an industry.

- tenant_customization:
  Client-specific settings on top of an industry template/package: logo, colors, legal details, document templates, field labels, workflow settings, notification settings, signature settings.

- live_client_hotfix:
  Minimal safe fix to an existing live project under Nginx, such as Trailers or Consulting Flask.

- migration_map:
  Mapping from legacy/live projects into future Flexity modules/templates/packages.

- documentation_only:
  Docs, plans, change requests, handoffs.

- research_only:
  Read-only audit, mapping, explanation.

## Live project guardrails

Trailers, Consulting Flask and Clinic App Flask are live/reference projects.

Clinic App Flask, Consulting Flask, Trailers Flask and Kindergarten are reference systems / validation directions. Flexity is the single main product. Common logic goes to universal modules, industry behavior to templates/packages, tenant-specific behavior to tenant customization only after approval.

Never:

- rewrite them from scratch;
- change architecture broadly;
- run deploy commands;
- run migrations;
- change Nginx/systemd;
- push to GitHub;
- remove files;
- run destructive git commands.

Allowed only after explicit approval:

- minimal hotfix;
- read-only mapping;
- documentation;
- test command;
- git status/diff/log.

